{"title":"MENTOR: Mixture-of-Experts Network with Task-Oriented Perturbation for Visual Reinforcement Learning","domain":"ROBOTICS","seeds":[{"problem":"Visual RL policies with shared MLP backbones suffer from gradient conflicts across subgoals/stages/tasks in complex robotic manipulation, leading to poor sample efficiency and suboptimal learning.","method":"Replace the policy MLP with a sparse Mixture-of-Experts (MoE) backbone conditioned on visual features. A CNN encoder maps images to latents; a router computes expert probabilities, selects the top-k experts, and combines their outputs with softmax weights, dynamically routing gradients to specialized experts to reduce conflicts (Sec. 3.1, Fig. 3–4). To prevent expert collapse, add a load-balancing auxiliary loss given by the negative entropy of the averaged expert-use distribution, which is optimized jointly with the actor (Appendix A, Algorithm 2). This design increases gradient compatibility and improves performance on multi-task and multi-stage settings."},{"problem":"Parameter perturbation helps visual RL agents escape local minima, but sampling perturbations from fixed random initializations ignores task structure, yielding inefficient exploration and unstable learning.","method":"Introduce a task-oriented perturbation mechanism that maintains a fixed-size buffer S_top of top-performing historical agents. Fit a Gaussian Φ_oriented = N(μ_top^θ, σ_top^θ) over their weights and periodically sample a candidate ϕ from this distribution to perturb the current agent. Blend weights via θ ← αθ + (1−α)ϕ, where α is set by the dormant-ratio-based schedule α = clip(1 − μβ, α_min, α_max) (Sec. 3.2, Alg. 1; Sec. 2). This yields perturbations biased toward promising regions, leading to faster skill acquisition and consistently lower, smoother dormant ratios than random-noise perturbations (Fig. 5)."}]}
